ECDF <- function(y_u){
  sapply(y_u, function(y){mean(y_u<=y)})
}

y = EDM.pop$goalsFor
plot(sort(y), ECDF(sort(y)), xlab="Number of Goals Scored", ylab="ECDF",  
     type = "s", col = "grey", lwd = 2, main="ECDF for Number of Goals Scored")

(c)

\[ \begin{aligned} l(\theta;\mathcal{P}) &= \log \left( L(\theta;\mathcal{P}) \right) \\ &= N\bar{y}(log(\theta)) - N\theta - \sum_{u \in \mathcal{P}}\log(y_u!) \end{aligned} \]

\[ \begin{aligned} l^\prime(\theta;\mathcal{P}) &= \frac{N\bar{y}}{\theta} - N \end{aligned} \]

To get \(\hat\theta_{MLE}\), we solve the following equation. \[ \begin{aligned} l^\prime(\theta;\mathcal{P}) &= \frac{N\bar{y}}{\theta} - N = 0 \end{aligned} \] Thus, the maximum likelihood estimate \(\hat\theta_{MLE} = \bar{y}\).

theta_MLE <- mean(y)
theta_MLE
## [1] 2.864625

(d)

(e)

(i)

We know \[F(y;\theta) =\sum_{k\leq y} \frac{\theta^ke^{-\theta}}{k!}\] for \(y,k\in\mathbb{Z}^{\geq0}\) and \(\theta>0\), so we get \[ \begin{aligned} \frac{dF(y;\theta)}{d\theta} &= \frac{d\left(\sum_{k\leq y} \frac{\theta^ke^{-\theta}}{k!}\right)}{d\theta} \\ &= \sum_{k=0}^y \frac{k\theta^{k-1}e^{-\theta}+\theta^k(-e^{-\theta})}{k!} \\ &= \sum_{k=0}^y \frac{k\theta^{k-1}e^{-\theta}}{k!} - \sum_{k=0}^y \frac{\theta^ke^{-\theta}}{k!} \\ &= \sum_{k=0}^y \frac{k\theta^{k-1}e^{-\theta}}{k!} - F(y;\theta)\\ &= \sum_{k=1}^{y} \frac{\theta^{k-1}e^{-\theta}}{(k-1)!} - F(y;\theta)\\ &= \sum_{m=0}^{y-1} \frac{\theta^{m}e^{-\theta}}{m!} - F(y;\theta) \space by\space letting \space m = k-1\\ &= F(y-1;\theta)-F(y;\theta) \end{aligned} \]

(ii)

\[ \begin{aligned} \psi(\theta;\mathcal{P}) &= \frac{d\left(\frac{1}{N}\sum_{u\in\mathcal{P}}\left[F(y_u;\theta)-F(y_u;\mathcal{P})\right]^2\right)}{d\theta} \\ &= \frac{2}{N}\sum_{u\in\mathcal{P}}\left(\left[F(y_u;\theta)-F(y_u;\mathcal{P})\right] \frac{dF(y_u;\theta)}{d\theta}\right) \\ &= \frac{2}{N}\sum_{u\in\mathcal{P}}\left(\left[F(y_u;\theta)-F(y_u;\mathcal{P})\right]\left[F(y_u-1;\theta)-F(y_u;\theta)\right]\right) \\ \end{aligned} \]

$$ \[\begin{aligned} \psi^\prime(\theta;\mathcal{P}) &= \frac{2}{N}\sum_{u\in\mathcal{P}} \left(\frac{dF(y_u;\theta)}{d\theta}\left[F(y_u-1;\theta)-F(y_u;\theta)\right]\right) + \frac{2}{N}\sum_{u\in\mathcal{P}} \left(\left[F(y_u;\theta)-F(y_u;\mathcal{P})\right]\left[\frac{dF(y_u-1;\theta)}{d\theta}-\frac{dF(y_u;\theta)}{d\theta}\right]\right)\\ &= \frac{2}{N}\sum_{u\in\mathcal{P}} \left(\left[F(y_u-1;\theta)-F(y_u;\theta)\right]^2\right) + \frac{2}{N}\sum_{u\in\mathcal{P}} \left(\left[F(y_u;\theta)-F(y_u;\mathcal{P})\right]\left[F(y_u-2;\theta)-2F(y_u-1:\theta)+F(y_u;\theta)\right]\right)\\ \end{aligned}\]

$$

(iii)

createMDEPsiFns <- function(y) {
  psiFn <- function(theta) {
    2 * mean((ppois(y, theta) - ECDF(y)) * (ppois(y-1, theta) - ppois(y, theta)))
  }
  psiPrimeFn <- function(theta) {
    2 * mean((ppois(y-1, theta) - ppois(y, theta))^2) +
    2 * mean((ppois(y, theta) - ECDF(y)) * (ppois(y-2, theta) - 2*ppois(y-1, theta) + ppois(y, theta)))
  }
  list(psiFn = psiFn, psiPrimeFn = psiPrimeFn)
}

The Horvitz-Thompson estimate of \(a(\mathcal{P}_H)\) is 4.743454, and the Horvitz-Thompson estiamte of \(a(\mathcal{P}_A)\) is 3.517202.

(ii)

estVarHT <- function(t_u, pi_u, pi_uv){
  ## t_u = an n element array containing the variate values for the sample
  ## pi_u = an n element array containing the (marginal) inclusion probabilities for the sample
  ## pi_uv = an nxn matrix containing the joint inclusion probabilities for the sample
  delta <- pi_uv - outer(pi_u, pi_u)
  estimateVar <-  sum( (delta/pi_uv) * outer(t_u/pi_u,t_u/pi_u) ) 
  return(abs(estimateVar))
}

pi_uvh <- 1-2*((Nh-1)/Nh)^nh + ((Nh-2)/Nh)^nh
pi_uva <- 1-2*((Na-1)/Na)^na + ((Na-2)/Na)^na

hvar <- estVarHT(t_uh, pi_uh, pi_uvh)
sqrt(hvar)
## [1] 0.7027197
avar <- estVarHT(t_ua, pi_ua, pi_uva)
sqrt(avar)
## [1] 0.4387212

The standard error for the estimate of \(a(\mathcal{P}_H)\) is 0.7027197. The standard error for the estimate of \(a(\mathcal{P}_A)\) is 0.4387212.

(iii)

var <- hvar+avar
sd <- sqrt(var)

HTavg <- HTavgh-HTavga
HTavg + c(-1,1) * sd
## [1] 0.3978252 2.0546792

The approximate 95% confidence interval for \(a(\mathcal{P}_H) - a(\mathcal{P}_A)\) is [0.3978252, 2.0546792].

(iv)

Since the confidence interval in part iii. does not contain 0 and 0.3978252 > 0, we conclude that there is presence of the so-called home ice advantage.

(c)

(i)

avepop <- mean(EDM.pop$goalsFor)
n = c(100,200,300,400,500,600,700,800,900,1000)
N <- nrow(EDM.pop)
sampbias <- rep(0,length(n))
sampvars <- rep(0,length(n))
sampmses <- rep(0,length(n))
sampcovs <- rep(0,length(n))

for(i in 1:length(n)){
  est <- rep(0, 1000)
  ci <- matrix(0, nrow = 1000, ncol = 2)
  pi_u <- rep(n[i]/N, n[i])
  pi_uv <- matrix((n[i]*(n[i]-1))/(N*(N-1)),nrow=n[i],ncol=n[i])
  diag(pi_uv) <- pi_u
  for(m in 1:1000){
    samp <- sample(EDM.pop$goalsFor, size = n[i], replace = FALSE)
    t_u <- samp/N
    est[m] <- sum(t_u/pi_u)
    se <- sqrt(estVarHT(t_u, pi_u, pi_uv))
    ci[m,] <- sum(t_u / pi_u) + 2*c(-1,1)*se
  }
  sampbias[i] <- mean(est-avepop)
  sampvars[i] <- var(est)
  sampmses[i] <- mean((est-avepop)^2)
  sampcovs[i] <- mean(apply(X = ci, MARGIN = 1, FUN = function(u){avepop >= u[1] & avepop <= u[2]}))
}
par(mfrow=c(1,4))
plot(n, sampbias, ylim = c(-0.01,0.01),type="l", main= "Bias vs. n", ylab = "Bias")
abline(h=0, col="orange", lty = 2)

plot(n, sampvars, ylim = c(0,0.03),type = "l", main= "Variance vs. n", ylab = "Variance")
plot(n,sampmses, ylim = c(0,0.03),type = "l",   main= "MSE vs. n", ylab = "MSE")

plot(n,sampcovs, ylim = c(0, 1),type = "l",main= "Coverage vs. n", ylab = "Coverage")
abline(h = 0.95, col="green", lty = 2)

(ii)

For this Horvitz-Thompson Estimator, we find that bias is generally around 0. No matter what n, sample size, is, Bias is around 0. As n, sample size, increases, the variance decreases and the MSE decreases. Coverage is around and close to 0.95 as shown in the plot.
